{
  "id": "study-uk-acid-001",
  "version": "1.0",
  "title": "UK Acid Rave \u2014 Hard Chemistry",
  "subtitle": "The drum machine that survived the warehouse",
  "annotation": "UK acid rave drums are built on two certainties: the kick hits every beat, and the snare hits with a clap layered on top on beats 2 and 4. The 909 combination of snare body plus clap crack is the sound. Hats run 8th notes with alternating velocity \u2014 downbeats slightly louder, creating a walking pulse. The open hat lands on the 'and' of beats 2 and 4, one 8th note after the clap, as if chasing it. The grid is straight \u2014 no shuffle. The groove comes from velocity and placement, not timing offset. The 303 bassline does the rhythmic heavy lifting; the drums are the floor beneath it.",
  "grooveProfile": {
    "swingFeel": "Straight grid. No shuffle. UK rave was metronomic by design \u2014 the machine quality was the aesthetic. Use the swing slider to add shuffle and hear how it changes the character.",
    "accentLogic": "Kick and snare/clap share equal weight. The open hat accents after the clap on the 'and'. Closed hat alternates between stronger downbeat hits (vel 2) and softer off-8ths (vel 1).",
    "microtimingTendencies": "Straight 16th note grid. The groove in classic 808 State, LFO, and early Prodigy is in the velocity programming, not the timing. Contrast with the Chicago/Detroit house grooves which use timing offsets."
  },
